english:
  title: Record of Strict Valley
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A Buddhist nun named Huayan Gok hung a tablet at her dwelling inscribed with 'Strict Valley.' The name was given by Chan Master Wuhak. She asked me to write a record for this place.

    I have heard that the Huayan teaching is a perfect doctrine encompassing all virtues, opening one school. The vast and the delicate, the great and the minute, the open and the blocked, the bright and the dark, the sentient and the non-sentient, the formed and the formless—all the way to affliction and liberation—return to one, without even a hair's breadth of difference. How then could there be distinction between male and female?

    Yet this teaching remains unclear to me. So let me speak instead of daily practice. Rising and sitting at their proper times, eating with restraint—this is the seriousness of daily life. Meditation practice has its method, and ritual chanting has its rules—this is seriousness within and without. Whether gathering with others or walking alone, maintaining a pure heart with unwavering dedication until the end of life—this is seriousness throughout.

    If none of these three things is neglected, one draws near to the Way. Zengzi once said, "Ten eyes watching, ten fingers pointing—how stern!" Indeed, the rigor of self-examination and reflection is what we call discipline.

    Strict Valley is a woman, not someone I can closely know or teach. Yet since the Lazy Monk approved her dedication to the meditation practice, surely all blessings will adorn her as we stand and await them. Are not the fifty-three friends of Huayan beyond this very path? Thus I write this record.
  footnotes:
    - The 'fifty-three friends' (53 sages) refers to the pilgrimage narrative in the Huayan Sutra, where Sudhana visits fifty-three teachers on his path to enlightenment—here used metaphorically to suggest all sincere practitioners of the Way.
    - Zengzi (曾子) was a principal disciple of Confucius, known for his teaching on moral vigilance and self-cultivation.
